<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06335142 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06335142 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Nobel Peace Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi, who has been held under housearrest in Burma, will be allowed to receive letters from her family, a Thaiofficial said Friday in Bangkok. Aung San Suu Kyi's British husband, MichaelAris, made the request for correspondence privileges. Aung San Suu Kyi, 46, isthe leader of Burma's pro-democracy opposition, which swept elections in 1990while she was under house arrest. Military leaders never honored the electionresults and instead have imprisoned opposition members.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JAILED NOBEL WINNER WILL BE ALLOWED MAIL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911130  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  88  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, November 30, 199100335142,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>